1 | Business Understanding ¶

The present report analyses the data collected from a company in the telecommunications sector, regarding customers who stayed or left their service or product. Customer churn, meaning the departure of customers to rival businesses, is a major problem for many industries, especially the telecommunications sector, where customers have a lot of choices and can switch easily. One way to analyze customer churn is to use machine learning, which is the application of algorithms and techniques that can learn from data and make predictions. Machine learning can help telecom companies build predictive models that can identify customers who are likely to churn, and provide insights into the factors that influence their decision. This can enable the companies to take proactive measures to retain their customers, such as offering incentives, discounts or personalized services.

  • Business problem: The telecommunications company wishes to understand the rate at which they are losing customers and why, which in turn can inform strategies to improve customer retention;
  • The business success criteria for analyzing telecom churn revolve around retaining customers by enhance customer loyalty, and thereby maintaining or increasing revenue;
  • Machine learning problem: The analysis of telecom churn using machine learning involves several steps, such as gathering customer data, preprocessing and exploring the data, selecting and training appropriate algorithms, evaluating and comparing the performance of the models, and interpreting and communicating the results. This analysis is a binary classification problem, where the goal is to predict whether a customer will leave the service (churn) or stay;
  • The Machine learning success criteria are to develop a predictive model that can accurately identify customers at high risk of churn, and provide actionable insights for retention strategies. Some of the metrics that can be used to measure the machine learning success criteria are:
    1. Accuracy - The proportion of correct predictions made by the model out of the total number of predictions: Accuracy is a simple and intuitive measure of how well the model performs, but it can be misleading if the data is imbalanced, meaning that one class (churn or not churn) is much more frequent than the other;
    2. Recall - The proportion of actual churned customers that are correctly predicted by the model out of the total number of churned customers: The model requires a high recall rate to avoid mislabeling churned customers as non-churned, particularly when the data is imbalanced. Standard algorithms may be biased towards the majority class, leading to poor performance on the minority class. This can pose a challenge since the minority class is the class of interest. Therefore, the goal is to develop a model that is able to retrieve the majority of churned customers within the training set, even if it means that some non-churned customers are incorrectly classified as churned. This trade-off is often acceptable because failing to identify a churned customer (a false negative) can be more costly than the additional follow-up with a customer incorrectly labeled as churned (false positives);;
    3. Precision - The proportion of predicted churned customers that are actually churned out of the total number of predicted churned customers: Precision is a measure of how well the model can avoid false positives, which are customers who stay but are predicted to churn. A high precision rate means that the model can reduce the cost of retaining customers who are not likely to churn;
    4. F1 score - The harmonic mean of precision and recall, which is a balanced measure that takes into account both false positives and false negatives: F1 score is a good metric to use when the data is imbalanced, as it can reflect the trade-off between precision and recall;
    5. Cost-effectiveness - The difference between the revenue gained from retaining customers and the cost of retaining customers: A high cost-effectiveness means that the model can identify customers who are worth retaining, and avoid wasting resources on customers who are not;
    6. Actionability - The degree to which the insights from the model can lead to concrete and feasible retention strategies: A high actionability means that the model can explain the factors that influence customer churn, and suggest ways to improve customer satisfaction and loyalty.

Reference: https://www.datascience-pm.com/crisp-dm-2/

5000 rows × 18 columns

The dataset contains 5000 entries and 18 variables, which are the following:

  • CHURN: Indicates whether the customer left the service;
  • ACCOUNTLENGTH: The length of time the account has been active;
  • INTERNATIONALPLAN: Whether the customer has an international plan, with calls and messages to other countries;
  • VOICEMAILPLAN: Whether the customer has a voicemail plan;
  • NUMBERVMAILMESSAGES: Indicates the number of voicemail messages that have been made by the customer;
  • TOTALDAYMINUTES: Number of minutes the customer spoke during the day;
  • TOTALDAYCALLS: Number of calls the customer made daily;
  • TOTALDAYCHARGE: The amount the customer will pay for calls or messages made during the day;
  • TOTALEVEMINUTES: Number of minutes the customer spoke during the evening;
  • TOTALEVECALLS: Number of calls the customer has made during the evening;
  • TOTALEVECHARGE: The amount the customer will pay for calls or messages made during the evening;
  • TOTALNIGHTMINUTES: Number of minutes the customer spoke during the night;
  • TOTALNIGHTCALLS: Number of calls made by the customer during the night;
  • TOTALNIGHTCHARGE: The amount the customer will pay for calls or messages made during the night;
  • TOTALINTLMINUTES: Total minutes of international calls;
  • TOTALINTLCALLS: Total number of international calls;
  • TOTALINTLCHARGE: Total charge for international calls and messages;
  • NUMBERCUSTOMERSERVICECALLS: Indicates the number of calls the customer made to the company's customer service staff to report a complaint.

The variables regarding 'charge' are in dollars as explained here https://data.world/earino/churn.

Regarding the variable "totalevecalls", in section 2.2, in the distribution plots analysis, it's explained why this variable wasn't considered the result of adding the values of the variables 'totaldaycalls' and 'totalnightcalls', but rather the number of calls in a different period of the day (evening).

The first column of the table above indicates that the minority class consists of churned customers and the majority class comprises 4293 observations, which account for 86 % of the total. The Account length variable can also be an important factor in churn analysis as it could reflect the customer’s loyalty. Customers who have been with a company for a longer period may be less likely to churn. However, the relationship between account length and churn is not clear-cut and can vary depending on other factors such as the quality of service, customer satisfaction, and competitive offers.

In the pairplot of "churn", "accountlength", "totaldayminutes", "totaldaycalls" and "totaldaycharge" variables, shown below, it is possible conclude that there doesn't seem to be a direct relation between "churn" and "accountlength", as the first graph shows that the distributions of accountlength by class have a similar range of values. The pairplot reveals some additional insights:

  1. The scatter plots in the second row, with account length on the yy-axis, show a clear higher density of “yes_churn” data for larger values of total day minutes and total day charge, regardless of the account length. As for total day calls, the data appear to be scattered randomly across the plot;

  2. The scatter plots in the first row, with total day minutes on the yy-axis, indicate a marked concentration of “yes_churn” data for larger values of total day minutes, regardless of the total day calls. There's a strong correlation with total day charge, with a noticeable cluster of “yes_churn” data for high values of both total day minutes and total day charge;

Correlation Matrix¶

Before building the correlation matrix, the variables “churn”, “internationalplan”, “voicemailplan” were transformed into binary format:

  • "churn": Indicates whether the customer left the service (1 if yes, 0 if no);
  • "internationalplan": Indicates whether the customer has an international plan, with calls and messages to other countries (1 if yes, 0 if no);
  • "voicemailplan": Indicates whether the customer has a voicemail plan (1 if yes, 0 if no).

Given that the majority of the quantitative variables exhibit a distribution that approximates normality, and considering that the binary variable is coded as 0 and 1, the application of Pearson’s correlation coefficient yielded an outcome that is similar to the point-biserial correlation coefficient.

Based on the analysis of the preceding table, the features that show a relatively higher degree of correlation with “churn” are: “internationalplan”, “totaldayminutes”, “totaldaycharge”, and “numbercustomerservicecalls”. These features have a correlation coefficient of around 0.20, which is usually regarded as a low to medium correlation.

Finally, the following pairs of features have a very high positive correlation:

  • "totaldayminutes" and "totaldaycharge" (correlation coefficient of approximately 0.99);
  • "totaleveminutes" and "totalevecharge" (correlation coefficient of 1.00);
  • "totalnightminutes" and "totalnightcharge" (correlation coefficient of approximately 1.00);
  • "totalintlminutes" and "totalintlcharge" (correlation coefficient of approximately 0.99);
  • "voicemailplan" and "numbervmailmessages" (correlation coefficient of approximately 0.95). A strong relationship between these variables was observed in the graph “Number of vmailmessages stratified by existence or nonexistence of a voicemail plan” at the start of section 2.3.

2.4 Brief summary ¶

The data is imbalanced, as shown by the fact that the minority class, which corresponds to the customers who have churned, accounts for 14 % of the total. Improper administration of this will lead to a model that is biased towards the majority class. In addition, as observed in the beggining of this section, the data is incomplete. Hence, these issues need to be addressed in section 3.

Finally, in section 3, the redundant variables will be removed.

3 | Data Preparation ¶

3.1 Data Cleaning ¶

Removing Redundant Variables¶

First, as previously stated, the redundant variables were removed. All "charge" variables were removed, due to the strong correlation they exhibited with their corresponding “minutes” variables. The selection of variables to be removed from these highly correlated pairs was arbitrary, since they had the same percentage of missing values. The "numbervmailmessages" variables was also removed, due to the strong correlation with "voicemailplan" and its zero values indicated the absence of a voicemail plan, as seen at the start of section 2.3.

4.1 Balanced Data ¶

The problem of data imbalance was addressed by applying undersampling, which reduced the number of instances in the majority class (‘not churn’) to equal the number of instances in the minority class (‘churn’) in the training set. This involved a random selection of a subset of examples from the majority class.

Nevertheless, the estimate of future prediction error will be obtained with the original distribution and without data leakage.

In [17]:
from imblearn.under_sampling import RandomUnderSampler

under_sampler = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=42)

x_trainb, y_trainb = under_sampler.fit_resample(x_train, y_train)
print(len(y_trainb),len(y_train))

It is noteworthy that the training set contains less than 30 % of the instances from the original training set, which could impact the variability of the results when performing cross-validation, due to the smaller data size.

def LogReg_balanced_CV(x, y, C=1.0, penalty='l1',solver='liblinear'):
    
    LogReg = LogisticRegression(C=C, penalty=penalty, solver=solver, class_weight='balanced', dual=False, fit_intercept=True,
                                intercept_scaling=1, max_iter=100, multi_class='ovr', n_jobs=1,
                                tol=0.0001)
    
    scoring = ['accuracy', 'recall', 'precision', 'f1']
    
    scores = cross_validate(LogReg, x_trainb, y_trainb, cv=5, scoring=scoring)
    
    print("Average Scores and Standard Deviation:")
    
    for name in scoring:
      score_values = scores['test_' + name]
      score_mean = np.mean(score_values)
      score_std = np.std(score_values)
      print("%0.3f %s with a standard deviation of %0.3f" % (score_mean, name, score_std))

Based on the criterion that a standard deviation that is more than 10% of the mean score is considered high, it can be concluded that: the model has low standard deviation for accuracy, precision, and f1 scores, which means that it is consistent and reliable for these metrics. However, the model has high standard deviation for recall, which means that it is variable and unstable for this metric. This could indicate that the model has difficulty in detecting the positive class in some cases. As explained at the beginning of this section, this phenomenon could arise from the reduction of the training set size.

def LogReg_balanced(x, y, C=1.0, penalty='l1',solver='liblinear'):
    
    LogReg = LogisticRegression(C=C, penalty=penalty, solver=solver, class_weight='balanced', dual=False, fit_intercept=True,
                                intercept_scaling=1, max_iter=100, multi_class='ovr', n_jobs=1,
                                tol=0.0001)
    
    LogReg.fit(x_trainb, y_trainb)
    y_pred = LogReg.predict(x_test)

    coef_df = pd.DataFrame(np.round(LogReg.coef_, 3), columns=x.columns)
    coef_df_transposed = coef_df.transpose()
    coef_df_transposed.columns = ['Coefficients (betas)']

    print(coef_df_transposed)
    print("Model intercept:", np.round(LogReg.intercept_, 3))

    nll_model = log_loss(y_test, LogReg.predict_proba(x_test))
    nll_null = log_loss(y_test, np.repeat(y_trainb.mean(), len(y_test)))
    pseudo_r2 = 1 - (nll_model / nll_null)
    print('Pseudo R square:', np.round(pseudo_r2, 3))
    
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    labels = ['no churn', 'churn']
    cm_display = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm, display_labels=labels)
    
    pos_class = 1 

    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    f1score = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    print("")
    print("")
    print("Scores for the testing set:")
    print('Accuracy score:', np.round(accuracy, 3))
    print('Recall score for the positive class:', np.round(recall, 3))
    print('Precision score for the positive class:', np.round(precision, 3))
    print('F1 score for the positive class:', np.round(f1score, 3))
    
    y_pred_1 = LogReg.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_pred_1)
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_1)
    print("")
    print("AUPRC & AUROC:")
    print('Area under the precision-recall curve:', np.round(auc(recall, precision),3))
    print('Area under the ROC curve:', np.round(auc(fpr, tpr),3))
    print("")
    print('Confusion Matrix: ')

To improve the performance of the logistic regression model, the threshold was adjusted to optimize the F1 score for the positive class in the testing set. The threshold is not a parameter of the model, but a decision rule that can be applied to the predicted probabilities to assign labels. The default threshold is 0.5, which means that the model predicts the positive class if the probability of the positive class is greater than 0.5. To use a different threshold value, the probability estimates were obtained using the predict_proba method, as shown in the code below. Important note: The threshold does not affect the estimation of the coefficients, but it affects the evaluation of the model’s performance on the test data.

print(len(y_trainb),len(y_train))print(len(y_trainb),len(y_train))print(len(y_trainb),len(y_train))

def optimalt_LogReg_balanced(x, y, C=1.0, penalty='l1',solver='liblinear'):
    
    LogReg = LogisticRegression(C=C, penalty=penalty, solver=solver, class_weight='balanced', dual=False, fit_intercept=True,
                                intercept_scaling=1, max_iter=100, multi_class='ovr', n_jobs=1,
                                tol=0.0001)

    LogReg.fit(x_trainb, y_trainb)

    y_pred_1 = LogReg.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]
    
    f1_scores = [f1_score(y_test, y_pred_1 > t) for t in np.linspace(0, 1, 101)]
    best_threshold = np.linspace(0, 1, 101)[np.argmax(f1_scores)]
    
    print('Optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 score:', np.round(best_threshold,3))
    
optimalt_LogReg_balanced(x, y, C=1.0, penalty='l1',solver='liblinear')

def LogReg_balanced_withthreshold(x, y, C=1.0, threshold= 0.62, penalty='l1',solver='liblinear'):
    
    LogReg = LogisticRegression(C=C, penalty=penalty, solver=solver, class_weight='balanced', dual=False, fit_intercept=True,
                                intercept_scaling=1, max_iter=100, multi_class='ovr', n_jobs=1,
                                tol=0.0001)
    
    LogReg.fit(x_trainb, y_trainb)
    
    proba = LogReg.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1] 
    y_pred = np.where(proba > threshold, 1, 0)
    
    pos_class = 1 

    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    f1score = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    print('Accuracy score:', np.round(accuracy, 3))
    print('Recall score for the positive class:', np.round(recall, 3))
    print('Precision score for the positive class:', np.round(precision, 3))
    print('F1 score for the positive class:', np.round(f1score, 3))

print("Scores with the default threshold:")

The image above shows the Decision Tree for this problem, and it is very clear to see that it has an overfitting problem. In order to overcome this problem we need to to: Pre-Prune and Post-Prone. In the first stage, the goal is to find the optimal parameters for the max_depth, min_samples_leaf and min_samples_split.

4.1.6 Support Vector Machines ¶

The model SVC is a class that performs binary (or multi-class) classification using support vector machines. The default values of the model SVC in scikit-learn are as follows: C = 1.0, kernel = ‘rbf’, degree = 3, gamma = ‘scale’, coef0 = 0.0, shrinking = True, probability = False, tol = 0.001, cache_size = 200, class_weight = None, verbose = False, max_iter = -1, decision_function_shape = ‘ovr’, random_state = None. The parameter class_weight='balanced' was employed in this section.

As before, cross-validation was used first, as illustrated below, to find the best parameters. After conducting several experiments, the parameters kernel='rbf', C=1, gamma=0.1 were found to be optimal. For the remaining parameters, the default values were used during the experiments.

In [ ]:
def SVC_balanced_CV(x, y, kernel='rbf', C=1, gamma=0.1):
    
    model = SVC(kernel=kernel, C=C, gamma=gamma, random_state=42, class_weight='balanced')
    
    scoring = ['accuracy', 'recall', 'precision', 'f1']
    
    scores = cross_validate(model, x_trainb, y_trainb, cv=5, scoring=scoring)
    
    print("Average Scores and Standard Deviation:")

    for name in scoring:
      score_values = scores['test_' + name]
      score_mean = np.mean(score_values)
      score_std = np.std(score_values)
      print("%0.3f %s with a standard deviation of %0.3f" % (score_mean, name, score_std))

def SVC_balanced(x, y, kernel='rbf', C=1, gamma=0.1):  
    
    model = SVC(kernel=kernel, C=C,gamma=gamma,random_state=42,class_weight='balanced',probability=True) 
    model.fit(x_trainb, y_trainb)

    y_pred=model.predict(x_test)

    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    labels = ['no churn', 'churn']
    cm_display = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm, display_labels=labels)
    
    pos_class = 1 # positive class

    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    f1score = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    print("Scores for the testing set:")
    print('Accuracy score:', np.round(accuracy, 3))
    print('Recall score for the positive class:', np.round(recall, 3))
    print('Precision score for the positive class:', np.round(precision, 3))
    print('F1 score for the positive class:', np.round(f1score, 3))
    
    y_pred_1 = model.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_pred_1)
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_1)
    print("")

    print('Area under the precision-recall curve:', np.round(auc(recall, precision),3))
    print('Area under the ROC curve:', np.round(auc(fpr, tpr),3))

Comparing the scores obtained in the training set with cross-validation and the testing set, we can see a discrepancy, especially in the precision and F1 score. This is due to the imbalanced class distribution in the testing set, as discussed earlier.

Based on these results, the SVC model has a high recall and a low precision for the positive class, which means that it tends to label more cases as positive than they actually are. Moreover, the F1 score is considerably lower than the accuracy.

The model also has a high area under the ROC curve, which means that it can discriminate well between the positive and negative classes. However, the area under the precision-recall curve is relatively low, reinforcing that the model has a poor precision-recall trade-off.

To improve the performance of the SVC model, the threshold was adjusted to optimize the F1 score for the positive class in the testing set. The SVC model uses a decision function to assign a score to each input, and then compares the score to a threshold to determine the predicted class. The default threshold is zero, meaning that any input with a positive score is predicted as the positive class, and any input with a negative score is predicted as the negative class. The threshold of zero is based on the assumption that the decision function is centered around zero, and that the classes are balanced. To determine the optimal threshold value, the probability estimates were obtained using the predict_proba method, as shown in the code below. The decision_function method was also tested, but it yielded a similar output. Therefore, it was not included in this report. [referencia: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58545711/how-to-set-a-value-for-a-specific-threshold-in-svc-model-and-generate-a-confusio, https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.svm.SVC.html.]

In [ ]:
def SVC_balanced_withthreshold(x, y, kernel='rbf', C=1, gamma=0.1):
    
    model = SVC(kernel=kernel, C=C,gamma=gamma,random_state=42,class_weight='balanced', probability=True)
    model.fit(x_trainb, y_trainb)

    y_pred_1 = model.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]
    
    f1_scores = [f1_score(y_test, y_pred_1 > t) for t in np.linspace(0, 1, 101)]
    best_threshold = np.linspace(0, 1, 101)[np.argmax(f1_scores)]
    print("Optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 score:",np.round(best_threshold,3))
    
    def predict_with_threshold(threshold=best_threshold):
        y_pred = (y_pred_1 > threshold)
    
        pos_class = 1 
    
        accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
        recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
        precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
        f1score = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)

        print('Accuracy score:', np.round(accuracy, 3))
        print('Recall score for the positive class:', np.round(recall, 3))
        print('Precision score for the positive class:', np.round(precision, 3))
        print('F1 score for the positive class:', np.round(f1score, 3))
    
    print("")
    print("Scores with the optimal threshold:")
    predict_with_threshold()

SVC_balanced_withthreshold(x, y, kernel='rbf', C=1, gamma=0.1)

Optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 score: 0.75

Scores with the optimal threshold:
Accuracy score: 0.902
Recall score for the positive class: 0.657
Precision score for the positive class: 0.652
F1 score for the positive class: 0.655

Based on the outputs, it seems that the SVC model performs better with the optimal threshold obtained in the predict_proba method then with the default threshold of zero for the decision function. The optimal threshold obtained achieves a higher accuracy, precision, and F1 score for the positive class, while the default threshold of zero for the decision function has a higher recall for the positive class. This means that the default threshold is more sensitive to the positive class, but also more prone to false positives. The optimal threshold obtained is more balanced and accurate in predicting both classes.

Reference: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/supervised_learning.html

def LogReg(x, y, C=0.2, penalty='l2',solver='liblinear'):
    
    LogReg = LogisticRegression(C=C, penalty=penalty, solver=solver, class_weight=None, dual=False, fit_intercept=True,
                                intercept_scaling=1, max_iter=100, multi_class='ovr', n_jobs=1,
                                tol=0.0001)
    
    LogReg.fit(x_train, y_train)
    y_pred = LogReg.predict(x_test)

    coef_df = pd.DataFrame(np.round(LogReg.coef_, 3), columns=x.columns)
    coef_df_transposed = coef_df.transpose()
    coef_df_transposed.columns = ['Coefficients (betas)']

    print(coef_df_transposed)
    print("Model intercept:", np.round(LogReg.intercept_, 3))

    nll_model = log_loss(y_test, LogReg.predict_proba(x_test))
    nll_null = log_loss(y_test, np.repeat(y_train.mean(), len(y_test)))
    pseudo_r2 = 1 - (nll_model / nll_null)
    print('Pseudo R square:', np.round(pseudo_r2, 3))
    
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    labels = ['no churn', 'churn']
    cm_display = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(cm, display_labels=labels)
    
    pos_class = 1

    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    f1score = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    print("")
    print("")
    print("Scores for the testing set:")
    print('Accuracy score:', np.round(accuracy, 3))
    print('Recall score for the positive class:', np.round(recall, 3))
    print('Precision score for the positive class:', np.round(precision, 3))
    print('F1 score for the positive class:', np.round(f1score, 3))
    
    y_pred_1 = LogReg.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]
    precision, recall, _ = precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_pred_1)
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_pred_1)
    print("")
    print("AUPRC & AUROC:")
    print('Area under the precision-recall curve:', np.round(auc(recall, precision),3))
    print('Area under the ROC curve:', np.round(auc(fpr, tpr),3))
    print("")
    print('Confusion Matrix: ')
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(3,5)) 
    cm_display.plot(ax=ax, cmap='Reds') 

LogReg(x, y, C=0.2, penalty='l2',solver='liblinear')

def optimalt_LogReg(x, y, C=0.2, penalty='l2',solver='liblinear'):
    
    LogReg = LogisticRegression(C=C, penalty=penalty, solver=solver, class_weight=None, dual=False, fit_intercept=True,
                                intercept_scaling=1, max_iter=100, multi_class='ovr', n_jobs=1,
                                tol=0.0001)

    LogReg.fit(x_train, y_train)

    y_pred_1 = LogReg.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]

    f1_scores = [f1_score(y_test, y_pred_1 > t) for t in np.linspace(0, 1, 101)]
    best_threshold = np.linspace(0, 1, 101)[np.argmax(f1_scores)]
    
    print('Optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 score:', np.round(best_threshold,3))

def LogReg_withthreshold(x, y, C=0.2, threshold= 0.2, penalty='l2',solver='liblinear'):
    
    LogReg = LogisticRegression(C=C, penalty=penalty, solver=solver, class_weight=None, dual=False, fit_intercept=True,
                                intercept_scaling=1, max_iter=100, multi_class='ovr', n_jobs=1,
                                tol=0.0001)
    
    LogReg.fit(x_train, y_train)
    
    proba = LogReg.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1] 
    y_pred = np.where(proba > threshold, 1, 0)
    
    pos_class = 1 

    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    f1score = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
    print('Accuracy score:', np.round(accuracy, 3))
    print('Recall score for the positive class:', np.round(recall, 3))
    print('Precision score for the positive class:', np.round(precision, 3))
    print('F1 score for the positive class:', np.round(f1score, 3))

print("Scores with the default threshold (0.5):")    
LogReg_withthreshold(x, y, C=0.2, threshold= 0.5, penalty='l2',solver='liblinear')
print("")
print("Scores with the optimal threshold (0.2):") 
LogReg_withthreshold(x, y, C=0.2, threshold= 0.2, penalty='l2',solver='liblinear')

By lowering the threshold, the model becomes more sensitive to the positive class, and increases the recall score significantly. Additionally, as expected, the f1 score is better with the optimal threshold, but remains low.

    plt.subplots(nrows = 1,ncols = 1,figsize = (7,7), dpi=200)
    tree.plot_tree(clf, fontsize=5, filled=True)
    plt.show()

plottree(clf)

The image above shows the Decision Tree for this problem, and it is very clear to see that it has an overfitting problem. In order to overcome this problem we need to to: Pre-Prune and Post-Prone. In the first stage, the goal is to find the optimal parameters for the max_depth, min_samples_leaf and min_samples_split.

To improve the performance of the SVC model, the threshold was adjusted to optimize the F1 score for the positive class in the testing set. As done in the 4.1.6 section (with the balanced data), to determine the optimal threshold value, the probability estimates were obtained using the predict_proba method, as shown in the code below. The decision_function method was also tested, but it yielded a similar output. Therefore, it was not included in this report.

In [ ]:
def SVC_withthreshold(x, y, kernel='rbf', C=10, gamma=0.1):
    
    model = SVC(kernel=kernel, C=C,gamma=gamma,random_state=42,probability=True)
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)

    y_pred_1 = model.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1]
    
    f1_scores = [f1_score(y_test, y_pred_1 > t) for t in np.linspace(0, 1, 101)]
    best_threshold = np.linspace(0, 1, 101)[np.argmax(f1_scores)]
    print("Optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 score:",np.round(best_threshold,3))
    
    def predict_with_threshold(threshold=best_threshold):
        y_pred = (y_pred_1 > threshold)
    
        pos_class = 1
    
        accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
        recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
        precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)
        f1score = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=pos_class)

        print('Accuracy score:', np.round(accuracy, 3))
        print('Recall score for the positive class:', np.round(recall, 3))
        print('Precision score for the positive class:', np.round(precision, 3))
        print('F1 score for the positive class:', np.round(f1score, 3))
    
    print("")
    print("Scores with the optimal threshold:")
    predict_with_threshold()

SVC_withthreshold(x, y, kernel='rbf', C=10, gamma=0.1)

Optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 score: 0.28

Scores with the optimal threshold:
Accuracy score: 0.911
Recall score for the positive class: 0.707
Precision score for the positive class: 0.678
F1 score for the positive class: 0.692

The results show that using the optimal threshold, obtained with the predict_proba method, improves slightly the recall and the f1 score for the positive class, compared to the default threshold for the decision function.

5 | Main Conclusions ¶

What is the best model and the recommended data science procedure for the business?¶

When comparing balanced and unbalanced data, unbalanced data achieved higher accuracy for both sets (training and testing), while the balanced data achieved higher f1 scores for the training set after crossing validation. Regarding the optimization with the threshold, the f1 scores are quite similar. As previously discussed, the cross-validation discrepancies are probably attributable not only to the data balancing but also to the adverse effects of this balancing, which result in a significant reduction of the data by under sampling the original dataset. Under Sampling was selected after examining both Under and Over sampling methods and their common uses.

Regarding all the different methods, on the balanced side of the problem, the XGBoostb Ensemble and SVM achieved an overall good performance, with all the scores above 0.800 after cross-validation within the training set, with the first one having the higher f1 score (0.857). Before and after optimization with a threshold within the testing set, the models with higher f1 scores were the Decision Trees and the XGBoosting Ensemble, with a f1 score of 0.753 and 0.785, respectively after optimization (the remaining scores are all above 0.650 for these models).

On the unbalanced side of the problem, after cross-validation within the training set, the Decision Trees, XGBoosting Ensemble and NNetwork achieved the best scores (all scores above 0.650). The best f1 score was achieved once again by the XGBoosting Ensemble model (0.802). Similar results were achieved within the testing set, being the XGBoost Ensembles model the one with the best f1 score and a good performance overall (with all scores above 0.750).

What can the business gain from these data science effort?¶

Looking only into the data science side of the problem, the business gains different working models, each one with its own best features, giving the company different possibilities to deploy based on their preferences. The chosen model for a given time does not have to be definitive and when the predictions start failing all models can be tuned again with new and more recent datasets since this report has built-in tunning functions for most models.

In general, after this initial step, the business would need deficient effort to maintain and optimize its activity in the future and with some adjustments, classification could go even further with some general classes:

  • For clients with a predicted_proba > .75 = high risk of churning, we can design a “strong” retention strategy. Since we expect few false positives, we can afford to invest in these clients with higher confidence.

  • Clients with predicted_proba between .5 and .75 = moderate risk of churning and “moderate” retention strategy.

  • Clients with predicted_proba between .25 and .5 = low risk of churning and “weak” retention strategy.

Reference: https://towardsdatascience.com/a-framework-for-analyzing-churn-370d2283b75c

What are the lessons learnt?¶

Even though the big image of data science revolves around modelling, evaluation and deployment, the first steps of CRISP-DM of Business Understanding, Data Understanding and Data Preparation are the ones that require most of the time and attention to progress further into the CRISP-DM cycle with ease.

This project shows that there is not a perfect model but a plethora of models that under certain circumstances can do a great job at modelling given problems under certain circumstances.

Despite the conclusions for the best model on the previous point, different business problems may require different models. For the same problem, different amounts of data can change the effectiveness of each model.

What is the summary of the achieved results?¶

Achieving high accuracy values for the models with reasonably high values for the recall and F1 score is a great success for this project. Some models ended up having low overall scores most likely because they are not the best for this problem in particular, due to imbalanced data or assumptions that do not hold.

Is there any particular characteristic of the data that makes the models difficult to classify?¶

While looking for the influence of each feature on the models, in both scenarios, the total calls for day, night and evening, and the customer account length had the lower impact on predicting the results. This could mean that these variables are not interesting to the problem, and add noise to the prediction since all models have false positives and false negatives.

What model would be chosen to explain how the model is doing it's predictions to the colleagues of the marketing department? And what would be the most accurate?¶

To understand how these models are doing their predictions we can take a look at the Bayesian Classifier. Naive Bayes is a technique that takes all features of a given dataset, assumes independence between them, and calculates the probability of each feature applying to each class. After this is done for the training set each entity of the test set will multiply the probability corresponding to each feature and that translates into one of the classes, giving the final classification.

Looking at the results obtained from each model, in balanced data and non-balanced data, the model that achieved the highest accuracy was the XGBoost Ensemble method.
